CF109BA644D449AFA2699A2344FE146D.description:
Identify people who
can help them in the
community (police,
firefighter, nurse).

781965EF5E7647DB8FD2603EF4F118C5.description:
Consistently
recognize and avoid
objects, substances,
and activities within
the environment that
might cause harm.

0D38D714616E4611A74DDE7C41581717.description:
Call a trusted adult when someone gets
injured or is in an unsafe situation.

FB57D55F6B8D41329295AB152CB4A3EC.description:
Usually recognize and avoid objects and situations that might
cause harm.

E7483AE9D310436FB0E89F163C1102B4.description: Know what their bodies can do, and play within their abilities to avoid injury to self or others.

BC07D7960DEF49C3B664DB80E20BBDAA.description:
With guidance, recognize and avoid situations that might
cause harm.

60892703733042ABA9E5599EAE256F83.description:
Increase self-control over their impulses (remind self not to touch something; wait for adult vs. running
ahead).

F8B78BC86BE843C5ABF777B9C64B6DB6.description:
Remember cause and effect experiences and apply their experiences to future situations (avoid touching cold railing, walk slowly down
steep hill where fall happened).

72050002B3D04F1FA937F3F33AE2D373.description:
Respond to simple
warnings that prevent
harm (“Stop!” “Hot!”
“Wait!”).

EE5B958DC0874DADA0E2D0775FD14E60.description:
Show some caution
about unfamiliar and/
or unsafe situations.

4ADA42B0AC5C4CB5B20947F9D9A28095.description:
Watch for adult
reactions to unfamiliar
things or situations
that might be
dangerous.

85B7E03CE2A94D638FDCCBA89EC1996C.description:
Notice and imitate
adults’ reactions
to new people and
situations.

FF66A92F9B7C4C5CB3C9A07E14D48A56.description:
Show trust in familiar
caregivers (calm down
with adult help, make
eye contact with
caregivers).

DC6A594CB42D4FFFB22E84DBCF3BAEFD.description: Children develop awareness of basic safety rules and begin to follow them.

F1004D38E16D47B0B7724AB16C3E3318.description:
Describe the value of
good health practices
(wash hands to get rid
of germs, drink milk to
build strong bones).

02636BD66DB140D6A8FC9135FF6D7449.description:
Perform tasks
to maintain the
indoor and outdoor
learning environment
independently.

A2911C66AD9C46A290C898F384C4BCDF.description:
Use adaptive equipment, ask for help with positioning
and movement, and/or
participate in medical
care routines as
needed.

C0D4DB5665D344209C7C390CC31F4B61.description:
Name people who help children
stay healthy.

B4ADF09D4A2047EEAB41D8778867FDC0.description:
Help with routine care of the
indoor and outdoor learning
environment (recycle, care for
garden).

9169CEA08E7B43C9BBAB5354A54C3C05.description:
Gain independence in hygiene
practices (throw tissues away
and wash hands, flush toilet).

77B52F4BFBEF49459FDFCD206C077BF2.description:
Follow basic hygiene practices
with reminders (brush teeth,
wash hands, use toilet, cough
into elbow).

B0E659F5E2F143009879E844340978F8.description:
Dress and undress themselves
with occasional assistance.

053D174258734FAC9FEEB743FD15D7D3.description:
Use adaptive equipment, ask for help with positioning and movement, and/or participate in
medical care routines as needed.

F09EE58CFA804A15A4E88F74981DA2A1.description:
Begin to take care
of objects (put toys
away, handle materials
carefully, water plants
or garden).

5E5F96CB59A444DEAA85401063FAC8BA.description:
Help with meal and
snack routines.

E78188BC0A3C4E6FBA0A7F37750BF243.description:
Initiate self-care
routines and complete
with guidance (put on
some clothes, undress,
throw away paper
towel, begin to show
an interest in toileting).

1C0118EAB7D640A38EF0A24B4D764C67.description:
Use adaptive
equipment, ask for
help with positioning
and movement, and/or
participate in medical
care routines as
needed.

8841AD77A79A4DEAB0E1D2A365FE92E8.description:
Drink from a cup
(with or without a lid)
and feed themselves
with their fingers or a
spoon.

818B5448E6FC4C8893AD0D6CAB436590.description:
Cooperate and help
with care routines and
cleanup (mouth care,
hand-washing,
diapering, dressing,
bathing).

F842D9E3E92140B3884F4747D2DB865A.description:
Show interest and
assist in routines
(open mouth for milk
or spoon, raise arms
for dressing).

1EDAF7A836204927A7D49F4DB9B82466.description:
Accept care
routines (mouth care,
handwashing,
diapering, dressing,
and bathing).

ADD50A04AA5841EBA712EA698EB9162F.description: Children develop independence in caring for themselves and their environment.

4940BA64E02F400187552C377AA5515F.description:
Consistently use
strategies to calm
themselves when
needed.

374E17E5B9104F2DA65808C3C3571981.description:
Use language to
ask adults or peers
specifically for the kind
of help needed in a
particular situation.

675FE0C0D523492A88BD56884A5D9920.description:
Use different
strategies to calm
themselves when
needed (self-talk,
deep breathing, cozy
corner).

40E14E20998E48F3808FA3967AC87E75.description:
Use words, signs,
or sign language to
ask for the things
they need (food when
hungry, drink when
thirsty, go outdoors
when they need to
be physically active).

CE284AF9F81C4BC28CEB7DAA3E2583C7.description:
Soothe themselves
when needed (find a
quiet area for alone
time, look at book
before nap).

2859B0F8ECB44E99973C087987818951.description:
Use words, signs,
or sign language to
ask for the things
they need (food when
hungry, drink when
thirsty, go outdoors
when they need to
be physically active).

82B207CDD7494784954FE84A21083656.description:
Use objects and
follow routines that
are comforting (get
their blanket and lie
down where they
usually sleep,
pick out favorite book
to be read before
lunch).

8827260397704E68B863BBB89430657C.description:
Use gestures,
words, signs, or
sign language to
communicate what
they need.

AAFEC27BC673498595178EBA2A307735.description:
Begin to soothe
themselves (suck
thumb, find pacifier,
reach for a security
object).

B132A582E72145B1B270D7191B802C1D.description:
Use different sounds
to let caregivers know
they need attention.

5184D581D4E24C4887C6B949D7EEB635.description: Children develop awareness of their needs and the ability to communicate their needs.

B6550ADA6A924A05864931149E28E7D5.description:
Use tools that require
strength and dexterity
of small muscles with
a moderate degree of
control (spray bottle,
hole puncher).

87FB21FE6E6F466999418F7CA1F51D43.description:
Engage in complex
hand-eye coordination
activities with a
moderate degree of
precision and control
(fasten clothing, cut
shapes, put together
small pieces).

AA64063A67114B35916F61857EE2F1E4.description:
Draw and write
smaller figures with
more detail (faces
with features, letters,
or letter-like forms).

68451A5CDF8547968A0196D08B1A2849.description:
Use tools that
require strength,
control, and
dexterity of small
muscles (forks,
crayons, markers,
safety scissors,
adapted tools).

497CB19775054017B8ADA9978474EB0F.description:
Engage in activities
that require hand-eye
coordination (build
with manipulatives,
mold Play-Doh®, work
puzzles with smaller
pieces).

3E37B94B0E9542AC87E33BAD50BCB476.description:
Draw simple shapes
and figures (square for
block, circles).

14C505F3BFD84D15AF9A77B5536898F2.description:
Use tools that require
finger and hand control
(large paintbrush,
measuring cups,
switches, shovel).

DF350E4E472748718EBF19E50BB72079.description:
Use hands and eyes
together with a
moderate degree of
control (complete
puzzles, thread beads
with large holes, use
shape sorters).

6BF603C4826F46D6925B56B94871B80B.description:
Use more complex,
refined hand
movements (stack a
few small blocks,
try to draw, turn pages
one at a time).

4ACE5B9099A04316A87AB74697D2F721.description:
Use simple tools
(spoon for feeding,
hammer with pegs,
crayon for scribbling),
however imperfectly.

A9D075A7D4C844BEB7635BEDF9D62039.description:
Use hands and eyes
together (put together
and take apart toys,
feed themselves
finger foods, fill
containers).

6965BA3D8B5F46138FBF07FFB721BF48.description:
Use hands to
manipulate objects
(stack two or three
large blocks, pick up
or roll a ball).

1C6AE2CA0A684604BD6E69AAC1BA072A.description:
Use a pincer grasp to
pick up an object with
finger and thumb.

1D36733A4F6B4F53A65B5E9B2DEAE145.description:
Transfer objects from
one hand to the other.

289CB8E158D149C8B9B691C31D872FD7.description:
Use both hands to
swipe at, reach for,
grasp, hold, shake,
and release objects.

499922215F3149C6B98D9A05FC071AEA.description:
Children develop small muscle control and hand-eye coordination to manipulate objects
and work with tools.

E94E72CB628741D386C7F2B5A936622C.description:
Show awareness of
own body in relation to other people and
objects while moving through space.

6508E6C817284E98BC8496F3DBF618CE.description:
Move quickly through
the environment and stop (run fast, pedal fast).

E23F21E668D148B0AE184319A842C53B.description:
Perform complex
movements smoothly
(skipping, balancing
on beams, hopping from one place to another).

935BBB31F47544C3AD7B08E79D0D7378.description:
Coordinate movement of upper and
lower body.

43117F0BF38C475DB777D77F8CE53A6C.description: Move in space with good coordination (running, hopping in place, galloping).

9BBE4F9CB32C49DCBE6A46A4278E5E72.description:
Demonstrate large muscle control
by throwing balls
accurately, sliding
down slides, pedaling riding toys, and using
assistive technology effectively.

BEA6DD56B8CA4DB9A996F46F9D77EF92.description:
Refine movements and show generally good coordination
(e.g., throwing and
catching).

E6E0D09D38184F478D451F2C845B019D.description:
Demonstrate strength and balance
by managing uneven surfaces such as hills, ramps, and
steps.

41A9A16A25F641C7A8D67C2006F81F5C.description:
Perform actions smoothly with balance, strength, and coordination (dance,
bend over to pick up a toy, reach up high on a shelf, walk up and
down steps).

0AD31902F1994A549F86E5E15D0D89E8.description:
Use familiar objects
that encourage large
motor movements
(riding toys, crawl tubes, large ball in
basket, slide).

DAFCD2ACE0194311951BF642E1145E8E.description:
Move through the
world with a variety of movements and with increasing
independence
(run, jump, pedal).

FD6FDCFAC99645C6A707CD1BCD8CB6AF.description:
Move arms and legs to complete a
task (kick, jump, step, pedal, push away).

A058F2C3F1CD4369806C2703A911060B.description: Move through the world with more independence (crawl, cruise, walk, run, use therapeutic walker).

8E3FA1BCFE2445B0B95444E22B88CCF3.description:
Move arms and legs together to climb,
push, and pull (push a stroller, use riding toys, crawl up steps).

FE318D9036D0432D8D225FA9D6374F8D.description:
Develop strength, balance, and coordination by repeating movements (pull up and sit down;
bend and straighten,
squat to pick
something up from the floor).

9B0B1F8BEE694EEC832E993BC9DA660F.description:
Move from place to place as their abilities
allow (squirm, roll,
scoot, crawl, cruise, or walk).

F9D04DAF9B414EED9B3B271F865F0DBC.description:
Move in and out of various positions by
rolling, pushing up,
and pulling to stand.

ECFEBA7A35264EF096AE4355F5704647.description:
Develop upright
posture when sitting
and standing.

70F94A3E10074BC796AD66FA402CE34F.description: Gain control of arm and leg movements.

F0E041B28C7242BAA4C2E9699A62C726.description:
Children develop the large muscle control and abilities needed to move through and
explore their environment.

1CBD0D2170A64DC0960C5A10D7B25D43.description:
Independently start
and participate in
sleep routines most of
the time.

9045CECA7B9E45048B071151ECA4BA10.description:
Communicate ways
sleep keeps us healthy
and makes us feel
good.

D40BE958194549878C35FA40279EBABE.description:
With increasing
independence, start
and participate in
sleep routines.

C36CDAC22A8141C88060CB52305C6025.description:
Recognize and
communicate signs of
being tired.

E6A240BC2BED4CFDA76C2B445BA9D952.description:
Learning to fall
asleep on their own.

DE257374DC454C11948255CBA6376C3E.description:
With guidance,
participate in sleep
routines (wash hands
after lunch, get blanket,
lie down on bed or
mat).

67B08EF0259048408BED2017DDF5878F.description:
Use language about
sleep (say, “Time for
bed,” after clearing
lunch things; give sign
for sleep).

C17E605483AC42E6B10801BE7CD1E53E.description:
Use simple sounds,
gestures, or words to
show they are tired
(say, “Night, night.”).

B297A30E415B4B89AABCF5CEFFE96EE6.description:
Cooperate with
sleep routines
(choose a book,
get preferred sleep
toy).

897CE9568D654BB8A937A4F6F5EBC958.description:
Develop a personal
sleep routine or
pattern.

400E1D45DAF849FE8439536DA26AEE6F.description:
Settle down and fall
asleep after a routine
that includes a familiar
series of events.

09A2632D285E492A9B8885BB333F18C0.description:
Sleep for longer
periods at a time
(more at night, and
less during the day).

566C19C816AA4C9C852CB09880E98987.description:
Transition
independently
from active to quiet
activities most of the
time.

8C734355746B4B30A8B8FBFAD6534C2B.description:
Participate in
structured and
unstructured motor
activities that build
strength, speed,
flexibility, and
coordination (red light,
green light; chase; free
play).

3E065C0FD7DB4F1F9EC174CA4E5518D2.description:
Communicate ways
physical activity keeps
us healthy and makes
us feel good.

4086886E496F478DA9AAE3BE46F5DC5F.description:
Develop strength and
stamina by spending
extended periods of
time engaged in active
physical play indoors
and out.

A8F84FEE887F461CB17F467DD5360E28.description:
Transition from
active to quiet
activities with limited
guidance and support.

1FE86124375C46D2864825D83BA60322.description:
Participate in simple
games and other
structured motor
activities that enhance
physical fitness (songs
with movement,
throwing and
catching).

EDE7D713BE7E43448E8F2A9B30FFCD66.description:
Choose a variety
of structured and
unstructured physical
activities indoors and
outdoors.

2637C6316D734FEBBCC12F493A859C65.description:
Develop strength and stamina by spending moderate periods of
time engaged in active
physical play indoors
and out.

A9339A103A034DADAD7C6DD7907403B7.description:
With guidance and
support, transition from
active to quiet
activities.

955DB3BDA1744C4AA962C1B2F75BE9D7.description:
Show satisfaction
with new active skills
and strengths (ask
others to watch them,
say, “I’m big and
strong!”).

5F1CA6887E8E45A6BD1BB8C6B41C1D10.description:
Develop strength and stamina by spending moderate periods of time engaged in active
physical play indoors
and out.

ED2FAFFD878C4DD39ACABBF39487CAC9.description:
Develop strength
and stamina as they
use large muscles
and participate in
physical activity for
longer periods of
time.

912EEE5D261641FF87A9B747359A0BDA.description:
Engage in regular
and sustained
movement (push toys
around play yard, go
up and down slide
over and over).

77BC68F822414A69A3BEA93775ADDEA2.description:
Anticipate and ask
for outdoor play (point
at door and say,
“Out!”, resist coming
indoors).

DA35C6E75B18498AA57D4C126BD9147D.description:
Show they enjoy
active play and seek
to be physically active
(choose to play often
on climber, laugh and
squeal while moving).

ED34F74E4E0B41689DEE5BA35E4E1A71.description:
Develop strength by
continuing movements
over short
periods of time.

0A0989FA5F9049DE96C987513B7D4938.description:
Move their bodies to
explore the indoor and
outdoor environment.

4A77DD4C46634A319D3CA8905B831DA0.description:
Engage in physically
active movements
(spending time on their
tummy, repeating
actions, kicking,
waving arms, rolling
over).

C8FACBBADC014A6099F92AEC6E0C914D.description: Children engage in and sustain various forms of physical play indoors and out.

6540138310BE4CAC9BD793783353C283.description:
Name foods and
beverages that help to
build healthy bodies.

F4E33856248340AF8EC0559B2F165E08.description:
Talk about variety
and amount of foods
needed to be healthy
(can identify what is
missing from their
meal).

BEAC34C9B61F495AAA8FD4F2873538DE.description:
Given a selection of
familiar foods, identify
which foods are
nutritious and which
are not.

7E4C9892D3554DA99B16ABB60502CBA8.description:
Communicate that
some foods are
good for them (fruits,
vegetables, milk) and
some are not healthy
(potato chips, soda).

F8A89E3E05504890B1410AF07E240009.description:
Notice and talk about
food preferences,
textures, temperatures,
and tastes (crunchy
crackers, warm
soup, sweet apples).

5F34C010656D4B508F9C6C006AD50216.description:
Eat foods depending
on their appetite and
personal preference
(make food choices
at a meal, leave
unwanted food on
plate, ask for seconds
of favorite food).

4A75AC07890647A8B43A88C65CCF3F37.description:
Feed themselves
using utensils and
hands.

0DA5279FD218424795EC09876A93F836.description:
Eat a variety of
small pieces of ageappropriate table
foods.

9F2E973F7FE843C69863D4A037300A59.description:
Eat enough to meet
nutritional needs,
even when the
amount or type of
food varies over time
(eat a lot at one meal
and little at the next,
show interest in many
foods but no interest
in others).

7A8D603E74D140C385F7D856BABE4B1E.description:
Ask for or accept
food when hungry.

6A3ADE15C8AC40AEA9927E2236243EDD.description:
Feed themselves
with some assistance
(may use hands,
spoons, or cups with
or without lids).

367DB4B2880940B98C3DDE0DEC3AD008.description:
Eat different kinds of
food such as liquids,
pureed or soft foods,
and finely chopped
food.

E3468601718547838FA47F0DA8917FF3.description:
Respond to different
textures of food in their
mouth (wait for the next
bite, spit out food, turn
head away).

B54BC17ED2354446B154387E821F1BD6.description:
Indicate foods they like
and do not like.

928862136F11463F85B2005DA6EB34B5.description:
Show hunger or
fullness using actions,
sounds, or words (cry
or search for food, turn
away when full).

74EAF835359C43AEBAC30D0A56049DFC.description:
Help with feeding
themselves (eat finger
foods, hold bottle).
